## REVIEW ARTICLE

## How useful is/uni00A0sentinel lymph node biopsy for/uni00A0the/uni00A0status of/uni00A0lymph node metastasis in/uni00A0cT1N0M0 gastric cancer? A/uni00A0systematic review and/uni00A0meta-analysis

Yuqiang/uni00A0Huang 1,2 /uni00A0· Mengting/uni00A0Pan 2 /uni00A0· Zhiwei/uni00A0Deng 1 /uni00A0· Yufei/uni00A0Ji 2 /uni00A0· Bo/uni00A0Chen 1,2,3

Received: 16 July 2020 / Accepted: 11 March 2021 © Italian Society of Surgery (SIC) 2021

## Abstract

Sentinel lymph node biopsy (SLNB) is intriguing because it is expected to further expand the indication of endoscopic resection (ER) for cT1N0M0 gastric cancer and as an additional operation for post-ER gastric cancer. The aim of our study was to perform a systematic review and meta-analysis on the feasibility and diagnostic value of SLNB technique in patients with cT1N0M0 gastric cancer. Eligible studies were systematically searched in PubMed, Embase, and Cochrane Library databases from inception to April 2020. A random-effect model was used to pool the data, and subgroup analysis was used to explain the heterogeneities. A total of 22 clinical studies (1993 patients with cT1N0M0 gastric cancer) were included. The pooled SLN identification rate, sensitivity, specificity, and diagnostic odds ratio with 95% confidence intervals were 0.99 (0.99-1.00), 0.92 (0.88-0.95), 1.00 (1.00-1.00), and 832.8 (395.5-1753.6), respectively. The summary receiver operator characteristic displayed a test accuracy of 99.3%. Subgroup analysis found an improved SLN sensitivity for studies with the mean number of SLNs > 4 and studies stained with a combination of hematoxylin-eosin with immunohistochemistry (HE + IHC). Further, studies using the basin dissection were associated with a higher SLN identification rate. The current meta-analysis provides data that favors the use of SLNB for predicting the status of lymph node metastasis in patients with cT1N0M0 gastric cancer. However, establishing standard procedure and suitable criteria for further application and optimization of SLNB is urgently needed.

Keywords Gastric cancer/uni00A0· Sentinel lymph node/uni00A0· Systematic review/uni00A0· Meta-analysis

## Introduction

Gastric cancer (GC) is now discovered in the early stages in many asymptomatic patients due to recent advances in endoscopic diagnosis. In Japan, the proportion of cT1 to

Endoscopic mucosal resection (EMR) and endoscopic submucosal dissection (ESD) are currently only performed for cT1aN0M0 gastric cancer, and standard gastrectomy with D1 or D1 + lymph node dissection is recommended for histologically undifferentiatedtype adenocarcinomas and cT1bN0M0 gastric tumors [2]. However, the rate of lymph node metastasis in patients with early gastric cancer (EGC) ranges between 15 and 20%. Many patients with EGC who actually have no lymph node metastasis undergo unnecessary lymphadenectomy, thereby increasing the duration of surgery and the incidence of complications [3-5]. Therefore, accurate evaluation of lymph node metastasis is crucial for the choice of treatment options and determining prognosis in patients with cT1N0M0 gastric cancer.

Sentinel lymph node (SLN) is defined as the first draining lymph node that receives lymphatic flow directly from the primary tumor, and the SLN concept identifies the SLN

![Image](data:image/png;base64,)

![Image](data:image/png;base64,)

as first site where lymph node (LN) metastasis emerges [6]. Therefore, it may be possible to ascertain the status of regional lymphatic flow by evaluating SLN pathology. At present, the concept of SLN has been validated in various solid tumors, such as breast cancer and melanoma [7, 8]. If the SLN concept can be applied in cT1N0M0 gastric cancer, or even in post-endoscopic resection stomach neoplasm, it may be possible to conduct minimally invasive surgery without reducing the curability, thus maintaining the postoperative quality of life (QOL). Sentinel lymph node biopsy to detect LN metastasis is expected to further expand the indication of EMR/ESD for cT1N0M0 gastric cancer and as an additional operation for gastric cancer after endoscopic resection, which is an attractive treatment strategy [9]. However, the clinical application and viability of sentinel lymph node biopsy (SLNB) in GC, especially in EGC, is still controversial due to the complexity of the lymphatic drainage network of the stomach and the possibility of micrometastasis or skip metastasis [10-12].

In the present study, we conducted a detailed meta-analysis on the feasibility and diagnostic value of SLNB technique to predict the status of LN metastasis in patients with cT1N0M0 gastric cancer. In addition, we aimed to identify technical aspects influencing the identification rate, the sensitivity of SLN mapping.

## Materials and/uni00A0methods

## Literature search

A comprehensive computer-aided literature search of PubMed, Embase, and Cochrane Library databases was carried out to find relevant publications concerning the diagnostic performance of SLNB in predicting LN status of cT1N0M0 gastric cancer. We used a search algorithm based on a combination of the terms: 'gastric cancer/neoplasm', 'stomach cancer/neoplasm', 'sentinel lymph node', 'sentinel node'. Both free text and MeSH search for keywords were used. The search was performed from the initiation of the databases to April 25, 2020. Reference lists from the included trials were screened to search for additional potentially relevant articles.

## Inclusion and/uni00A0exclusion criteria

Inclusion criteria were as follows: (1) studies investigated the diagnostic performance of SLNB in predicting LN status of cT1N0M0 gastric cancer; (2) regional lymphadenectomy was performed in keeping with regional guidelines; (3) intra-/postoperative histological examination of surgically resected specimens; (4) the SLN identification rate, sensitivity and specificity could be calculated.

![Image](data:image/png;base64,)

Studies were excluded on the basis of the following criteria: (1) patient was diagnosed as cT2-4 gastric cancer or LN metastasis or distant metastasis by preoperative examination; (2) articles were case reports, reviews, abstracts, metaanalyses, technical notes, or letters; (3) in/uni00A0vitro studies and animal experiments.

## Data extraction

Two investigators (YH and MP) independently reviewed the titles and abstracts of the retrieved articles based on the aforementioned selection criteria. Articles were excluded if clearly ineligible. Then the full-text versions of selected articles were evaluated to determine their eligibility for inclusion. Finally, the above two reviewers cross-examined each independently selected study. Predefined tables were used to extract data: first author, year of publication, sample size, type of study, tracers, tumor diameter, injection methods, surgical methods, mean number of detected SLNs, pathological methods, biopsy methods, and outcomes (identification rate, sensitivity, specificity).

## Quality assessment

Methodological quality of the eligible included studies was assessed by two independent reviewers (ZD and YJ) using the Quality Assessment of Diagnostic Accuracy Studies-2 (QUADAS-2) tool [13]. This tool evaluates the risk of bias and applicability of diagnostic accuracy studies based on 4 domains: patient selection, index test, reference standard, and flow and timing. Any discrepancies were resolved through discussion.

## Statistical analysis

The random-effects model based on the DerSimonian and Laird method was applied to pool the SLN identification rate, sensitivity, specificity, and diagnostic odds ratio (DOR) with 95% confidence interval (CI) [14]. The summary receiver operator characteristic (SROC) curve was constructed to estimate the overall accuracy by the area under the curve (AUC) and the Q * index. A preferred test has an AUC close to 1, while a poor test has an AUC close to 0.5 [15]. Heterogeneity among those included studies was quantified by the I 2 test, and I 2 values less than 25% correspond to mild heterogeneity [16].

Additional subgroup analysis to describe heterogeneity and further characterize outcomes was completed for mean number of SLNs, biopsy method, injection method, pathological staining, surgical method, tumor diameter. A Z -test was performed to analyze the statistical differences between independent groups. P < 0.05 was considered statistically significant.

Potential publication bias was evaluated by Deeks' funnel plots asymmetry test [17]. All statistical analyses were performed using Meta-Disc software Version 1.4 (Javier Zamora, Madrid, Spain) and Stata software Version 16.0 (Stata Corporation, College Station, TX, USA).

## Results

## Study selection and/uni00A0description

A total of 758 records were screened in the primary literature search. After each step of eliminating the ineligible studies, 22 studies including 1993 patients were finally selected according to the eligibility criteria [1, 3, 18-37]. The flow diagram of the literature search is shown in Fig./uni00A01.

Of the 22 included studies, 1993 patients were diagnosed with cT1N0M0 gastric cancer by preoperative examination, and most of them had tumors smaller than 40/uni00A0 mm in size. Included studies were published from 2003 to 2020, and 21 studies were conducted in Japan, 1 in Korea, and 1 in China. The characteristics of included studies are listed in Table/uni00A01.

## Quality assessment

The methodological quality of eligible studies was assessed using QUADAS-2 tool, and the results (Supplementary Fig./uni00A01) suggested that all included studies were of moderately high quality. Of these included studies, the author's judgement for risk of bias depicted a high risk of bias in 3 (13.6%) studies according to patient selection, while 2 (9.1%) studies had a high risk of bias according to the index test. Risk of bias regarding reference standard was unclear in only 3 (13.6%) studies while 19 (86.4%) studies were low risk. Only two (9.1%) studies showed a high risk of bias according to the flow and timing. With regards to the applicability of the studies, 86.4%, 91%, 95.5% of the studies had low concerns in patient selection, index test, and reference standard. Deeks' funnel plot showed potential publication bias between studies (Supplementary Fig./uni00A02).

## Subgroup analysis

The results of subgroup analyses are presented in Table/uni00A02. Factors significantly associated with SLN sensitivity were the following: the mean number of SLNs > 4 subgroup exhibited a significantly higher sensitivity than SLNs /uni2264 4 subgroup (0.94 vs 0.75, P = 0.009). Studies stained with a combination of hematoxylin-eosin with immunohistochemistry (HE + IHC) demonstrated an improved sensitivity when

compared to studies with HE only (0.99 vs 0.87, P = 0.002). No other factors significantly associated with SLN sensitivity were found (Table/uni00A02). Factors significantly associated with SLN identification rate were the following: studies using the lymph basin dissection (LBD) method demonstrated an improved SLN identification rate compared to studies using the pick-up method (1.00 vs 0.98, P = 0.013). No other factors significantly associated with SLN identification rate were found (Table/uni00A02).

## Discussion

To our knowledge, this is the first meta-analysis on the feasibility and diagnostic performance of SLNB technique to predict the status of LN metastasis in patients with cT1N0M0 gastric cancer.

Fig. 4 Summary receiver operator characteristic curve

![Image](data:image/png;base64,)

Sentinel lymph node biopsy to detect LN metastasis is expected to further expand the indication of endoscopic resection (ER) for cT1N0M0 gastric cancer and as an additional operation for post-ER gastric cancer. In the present study, we included 22 studies (1993 patients) with a high

pooled SLN identification rate, sensitivity, specificity, and diagnostic odds ratio, and the methods of AUC calculation also exhibited its favourable diagnostic performance. Overall, we considered that the results of SLNB in cT1N0M0 gastric cancer were satisfactory.

The problem of false-negative result of SLN biopsy in GC is an essential factor that limits its clinical application. Once a false-negative result occurs, it may lead to an inadequate lymphadenectomy, and then affect the cure rate of tumors. As reported by Lee et/uni00A0al. [38], they found that the risks of false-negatives for SLNB in GC decreased with the detection of more SLNs. Thus, we would like to place emphasis on the average number of SLNs and to evaluate its influence on the parameters of sensitivity and identification rate. In the subgroup analysis, our result showed that the number of harvested SLN was found to be the key factors affecting sensitivity, and the SLNs > 4 subgroup exhibited a significantly higher sensitivity than SLNs /uni2264 4 subgroup (0.94 vs 0.75, P = 0.009). These results reveal the lymphatic system of the stomach is complicated, with diverse flow directions and frequent skip metastasis, and SLN mapping may be limited by multiple SLNs and aberrant drainage pathways [11, 39]. Therefore, SLNs should be harvested as much as possible in the clinical application of SLN biopsy of GC, and we believe that at least 4 SLNs harvested should be recommended.

The gastric lymphatic basin was a relatively wide area defined as the lymphatic zones divided by the stream of the stained lymphatic canals, and LNs were divided into five basins along the main gastric arteries [40, 41]. As shown in previous studies, lymphatic basin dissection (LBD) was considered a selective lymphadenectomy procedure for resecting basins en-bloc, and its major advantage was the ability to capture missed LNs, thereby decreasing the concern of intraoperative false-negative SLNs [42]. Thus, the LBD seemed more preferable than the pick-up method. Moreover, Lee, YJ et/uni00A0al. attempted to evaluate the differences between LBD and pick-up methods of SLN biopsy in GC and found the detection rate was 96% and 54.8%, the sensitivity was 85.7% and 66%, respectively [43]. Our study further supported this view that LBD should be proposed as a standard technique to harvest the SLN, and subgroup analysis found that the LBD subgroup had a significantly higher SLN identification rate than the pick-up subgroup. However, there are some practical difficulties concerning LBD. Firstly, LBD increases the number of lymph nodes that require intraoperative pathological examination, which prolongs operation time. Secondly, excessive LBD could affect minimal gastric resection. Therefore, this method should be performed in the hands of an experienced surgeon.

As for SLN biopsy in GC, the most critical issue is the intraoperative frozen tissue section evaluation of SLNs for gastric cancer. Currently, HE staining was performed in most studies for the rapid intraoperative diagnosis of LN metastasis during operations. Unfortunately, the Japan Clinical Oncology Group multicenter trial JCOG0302 study was forced to terminate owing to the high FN results of the intraoperative pathologic examination [46]. Thus, it is very paramount to accurately assess LN metastasis (even to the level of micrometastasis) by intraoperative frozen section evaluation of SLNs. By our subgroup analysis, studies stained

Previous studies reported that, lymphatic vessels connected to each other through branches of the stomach wall which expand vertically, and the submucosal (SM) lymphatic vessels communicated freely with the subserosal (SS) and intermuscular lymphatic networks [44]. Therefore, the tracer injected under the serosa may diffuse in the same way as the tracer injected submucosally. In the subgroup analysis, a result consistent with the prospective study conducted by Lee et/uni00A0al. [45] was obtained, that no significant difference was found between patients using the SM and SS injection method in SLNB with regards to identification rate and sensitivity. Nevertheless, we believe that the SM injection method is more preferable with its simple procedure and short operation time. Additionally, patients with cT1N0M0 gastric cancer whose primary lesions are not always accessible from the serosal side, and it is arduous to accurately locate the primary lesion and inject a tracer through the subserosal approach.

with HE + IHC exhibited a higher sensitivity than that of studies with HE alone, which indicated that IHC used to detect micrometastases including isolated tumor cells (ITCs) was feasible [47]. However, given the limited time available, such examination cannot be performed on all SLNs harvested during surgery. Therefore, a simpler and easier method of improving intraoperative diagnostic precision is needed for the accurate and fast diagnosis of SLN metastasis. Recently, the developed reverse transcription-polymerase chain reaction (RT-PCR) and the one-step nucleic acid amplification assay (OSNA) have been performed to provide a more accurate and rapid intraoperative diagnosis of LN metastasis and micrometastasis, but these methods are also limited by cost and feasibility [48-50].

Theoretically, deeper tumor tissue infiltration may be related to larger tumor size, and further results in blockage of lymphatic vessels, thus affecting the diagnostic efficiency of SLN biopsy. Additionally, it was reported by a previous study that larger and more invasive tumors increased rates of LN metastasis and the potential for skip metastasis [10]. In the results of the subgroup analysis, we found a slightly higher pooled sensitivity of diameter /uni2264 30/uni00A0mm subgroup than that of diameter > 30/uni00A0mm subgroup. However, no more exploration was performed due to the limited information on the measurement of tumor diameter in all the original articles.

With the development of laparoscopic instruments and the improvement of the experience of surgeons, laparoscopic surgery showed more preferable than traditional open surgery by reducing operative blood loss, hospital stay time, and postoperative pain as well as improving postoperative quality of life [51]. Besides, individualized minimally invasive approach and functional preservation surgery has been a new strategy for the treatment of gastric cancer [52]. Laparoscopic gastrectomy combined with SLN biopsy may enhance these advantages and improve the patient's treatment options and postoperative quality of life. By our subgroup analysis, laparoscopic subgroup showed a slightly higher sensitivity than the open subgroup, which may be explained by the more detailed observation of SLNs with visual magnification during the laparoscopic surgery. In addition, laparoscopic series are more recent than open ones and the experience of surgeons and application frequency would improve with time, which may be a confounding factor for the better performance of laparoscopic surgery in this field than open surgery. However, these results still need to be confirmed in more clinical studies.

This meta-analysis contains several limitations. First, despite our attempts to include all relevant studies, Deeks' funnel plot asymmetry test still showed potential publication bias, which may limit the stability of the pooled result. Second, all the included studies were submitted from Asia, and the performance of this subject was uncertain in other

regions. Third, the SLN detection method was not uniform, as single or dual tracers, and radioisotope or/and dye were used, and all of which would affect the diagnostic performance of SLN biopsy.

## Conclusion

The current meta-analysis provides data that favors the use of SLNB for predicting the status of lymph node metastasis in patients with cT1N0M0 gastric cancer. However, due to the complexity of gastric lymphatic drainage, there are some practical difficulties concerning SLNB. First, excessive LBD could affect minimal gastric resection and increase intraoperative pathological examination time. Second, the issue of intraoperative metastasis detection remains to be resolved. Therefore, establishing standard procedure and suitable criteria for further application and optimization of SLNB is urgently needed. Finally, we hold the opinion that our results must be viewed with caution before an accurate and effective method occurs and further multicenter prospective clinical studies in different countries should be conducted to confirm the oncologic safety of this technique in the future.
